Basing one's economy on a single crop, as in Cuba, is not an economically prudent measure.  When the Iron Curtain fell, Cuba was in a terrible position economically.  The Soviet Union was a consistent buyer of their product (sugar), and they were not dependent on the world commodity market.  Exit the USSR and enter the global economy.  For the previous 5 years there was a glut on sugar on the world market.  The price of sugar fell and fell, they can't get the needed hard currency so who does Cuba blames, the USA.  Hmm, why not Indonesia, Brazil, Australia, the  Philippines and the other sugar producers?  In the USA, cane sugar was steadily falling out of favor, sugar production falls, fields are turned in condominiums, golf courses and also to green vegetables. Sugar refineries start closing and work a less than full capacity in the US because of the world sugar glut.  But the USA is blamed for Cuba's inability to get a decent price on the world market when that self same industry in the USA is in a bad state of decline and was not being propped up by the government (Reagan, not Clinton).<br>
<br>
I have friends of some repute in the organic agriculture area.  Cuban farmers have made great strides in the use of composts and other organic growing methods.  These processes are being studied and used in many third world countries.  But the centralized economy is still riding that dieing horse, old Sugar Cube.  Besides tourism, I can't see where Cuba can go for hard currency while still hitched to the sugar train.<br>
