<br>
Someone asked why people dislike the US.  I'm trying to see things from their side.  You know, show a little empathy.  Trying to understand is a good thing.<br>
<br>
When we provide support to &quot;freedom fighters&quot; in South America, how do you think the elected officials of that country feel about us?  How about the innocent people who are hurt in the conflict?<br>
<br>
Whether it was right or wrong is a completely separate issue.  What IS clear is that you can't support revolution (which is what we're doing) without making some people very angry with you.<br>
<br>
Take the other side -- support dictatorial regimes as I've mentioned before.  Now, how do you think people who oppose that regime are going to feel?  They are also not going to like us.<br>
<br>
The no-fly zone in Iraq to protect the Kurds -- how do you think we would have reacted in WW II if England had try to enact a no-fly zone over California to protect the Japanese that were being huddled into camps?<br>
<br>
(And don't start on me about how they aren't the same thing.  That's irrelevant.  What's relevant is how you would feel if a foreign government told the U.S. where we could fly our planes within our own borders.)<br>
<br>
===<br>
<br>
It's all well and good to stand up and wave the flag.  You just have to close your eyes and your minds and deny mistakes.<br>
<br>
Well I'm sorry, but everyone makes mistakes.<br>
<br>
And sometimes you're left with decisions that you just don't like.<br>
<br>
Imagine terrorists are holding a bunch of prisoners.  You can send in the SEALs with a high degree of success, but you suspect a couple of hostages will die.  You're sure that MORE hostages will die if you do nothing.<br>
<br>
SOMEONE will think you're wrong whatever you do.<br>
<br>
===<br>
<br>
I'd like to add a little something I thought about this morning about all this -- why the U.S. went into Kuwait.  Think about a few things.<br>
<br>
1. The U.S. knew about Iraq's weapons programs, including efforts to produce atomic weapons (and other nasty things).<br>
<br>
2. No sane individual (translation: anyone who agrees with me) would imagine Iraq having these capabilities is a good thing.  Especially if you live in Israel.<br>
<br>
3. As I recall events from 10 years ago, shortly before Iraq invade Kuwait, Saddam Hussein was given the impression the U.S. would turn a blind eye to agression in the area.  I don't remember where I heard this, but it was was of the reputable news sources.<br>
<br>
Now, link those three facts.<br>
<br>
Makes you think real hard, doesn't it?<br>
<br>
Makes you wonder if Saddam Hussein wasn't suckered into giving us an excuse to invade and destroy their weapons capabilities.<br>
<br>
===<br>
<br>
Now, let's say that that's exactly what happened.  For the sake of argument.  Was it wrong?<br>
<br>
Consider the alternative -- Iraq with nuclear and biological weapons, perhaps with advance delivery capability.<br>
<br>
Would the U.S. be snow white in this case?  Hmm.  Maybe, if it's snow a couple of days after the city spread salt and sand around.<br>
